223
00:24:00,048 --> 00:24:02,902
Too bad, Henri, I adore know-it-alls.

224
00:24:07,346 --> 00:24:09,258
So, where are you off to?

225
00:24:10,028 --> 00:24:12,842
Some place better food...
my apartment.

226
00:24:14,292 --> 00:24:15,294
And yourself?

227
00:24:16,134 --> 00:24:20,579
Back to the party.
I just wanted to spend 27 floors with you.

228
00:24:21,049 --> 00:24:23,932
- Well, that was a risky move.
- What?

229
00:24:24,624 --> 00:24:27,616
Leaving your date upstairs.
I hope it was worth it.

230
00:24:27,727 --> 00:24:28,829
What are you talking about?

231
00:24:28,855 --> 00:24:30,815
Oh, come on, that
beautiful woman in blue.

232
00:24:30,940 --> 00:24:33,472
Does her name happen to end in "kova"?

233
00:24:34,483 --> 00:24:38,337
No, her name is Agnes Boggs.

234
00:24:38,448 --> 00:24:40,970
Her uncle's the chef,
I'll let him know you liked his food.

235
00:24:42,602 --> 00:24:43,903
And she's not my date.

236
00:24:50,410 --> 00:24:53,059
- Taxi, Ma'am?
- Yes, please, thank you.

237
00:24:57,926 --> 00:24:59,008
Good night.

238
00:25:01,170 --> 00:25:02,290
I'll just wait with you.

239
00:25:02,402 --> 00:25:04,513
So you can find out where I live?

240
00:25:06,184 --> 00:25:08,267
It does make it a lot
easier to send flowers.

241
00:25:10,910 --> 00:25:12,811
Thank you, but I'll manage.

242
00:25:15,484 --> 00:25:18,007
Goodbye, it's been an
adventure meeting you.

243
00:25:21,351 --> 00:25:22,612
Thank you.

244
00:25:24,683 --> 00:25:25,684
Wait!

245
00:25:27,155 --> 00:25:30,569
There you go again, putting your
hand in places it doesn't belong.

246
00:25:32,171 --> 00:25:35,912
- How do we get in touch?
- Happy New Year, Ellis.

247
00:25:36,306 --> 00:25:37,567
Thank you, Sir.

248
00:26:02,050 --> 00:26:04,673
- Am I late?
- No more than usual.

249
00:26:05,694 --> 00:26:06,776
Happy Birthday, Mama.

250
00:26:07,696 --> 00:26:08,698
Thank you, Darling.

251
00:26:11,401 --> 00:26:13,413
I'm so happy to see you.

252
00:26:17,457 --> 00:26:19,519
You know you don't have
to still give me cards.

253
00:26:21,820 --> 00:26:24,634
- I love you.
- I love you, too.

254
00:26:26,117 --> 00:26:29,388
- So, when you are moving back up?
- The third week in February.

255
00:26:29,499 --> 00:26:31,259
- Right on schedule.
- Of course.

256
00:26:38,057 --> 00:26:40,356
I see you already forgot our
little talk about sodium.

257
00:26:40,990 --> 00:26:43,623
No, I am simply choosing to ignore it.

258
00:26:46,945 --> 00:26:52,561
Actually, I'm thinking of moving, myself.

259
00:26:54,513 --> 00:26:55,994
But you love where you live.

260
00:26:56,174 --> 00:26:59,127
I do, but, you know,
there's just too many stairs.

261
00:26:59,778 --> 00:27:05,284
Last week Kay Alfonso fell,
and she broke her hip.

262
00:27:05,365 --> 00:27:08,498
The doctor said she might
never leave the hospital.

263
00:27:10,269 --> 00:27:13,932
And the very next day,
Molly Andrews called me,

264
00:27:14,012 --> 00:27:19,568
and she told me about this wonderful
retirement community in Arizona.

265
00:27:19,638 --> 00:27:23,515
She moved in last spring. She said she's
never been happier in her whole life.

266
00:27:27,436 --> 00:27:28,587
What's a matter?

267
00:27:31,009 --> 00:27:34,113
We bought in Oregon so
that I could be close to you.

268
00:27:34,943 --> 00:27:36,455
You could come up for long visits,

269
00:27:36,566 --> 00:27:38,617
move in with me eventually.

270
00:27:40,329 --> 00:27:43,712
We haven't lived together
since I was in high school.

271
00:27:43,863 --> 00:27:46,486
A little bit.
You're not getting any younger.

272
00:27:47,366 --> 00:27:50,249
What if you move to Arizona
and something happened to you?

273
00:27:50,349 --> 00:27:51,351
What if you get sick?

274
00:27:52,131 --> 00:27:55,305
Then, I would hope that you'd
come and take care of me.

275
00:27:59,388 --> 00:28:00,663
What if I'm too late?

276
00:28:00,809 --> 00:28:07,507
No, no, we cannot do this,
not on your birthday, it's a holiday.

277
00:28:13,542 --> 00:28:16,605
I nearly fell off my feet.

278
00:28:16,705 --> 00:28:18,220
What are you two clucking about?

279
00:28:18,357 --> 00:28:21,271
Major news!
Mr. Jones is donating fifty thousand

280
00:28:21,323 --> 00:28:24,282
dollars worth of first edition
classics to this library.

281
00:28:24,354 --> 00:28:26,615
- What books, do you know?
- We're going to find out very soon,

282
00:28:26,695 --> 00:28:31,130
because his office called to say
that he'll be here to deliver them himself.

283
00:28:32,511 --> 00:28:34,943
- Hi.
- Oh no. - I'm Ellis. - Oh, good.

284
00:28:34,983 --> 00:28:37,134
- Welcome, - Thanks.
- Mr. Jones.

285
00:28:37,184 --> 00:28:40,365
On behalf of the San
Francisco Heritage Society

286
00:28:40,414 --> 00:28:44,923
I'd like to express our sincere
gratitude for your most generous gift.

287
00:28:45,013 --> 00:28:47,626
I left them in Shipping and Receiving,
but I'm sure they'll be right up.

288
00:28:47,707 --> 00:28:51,230
If you don't mind, we'd like
a photograph of you donating the books.

289
00:28:51,300 --> 00:28:52,432
Yeah, yeah, sure, sure.

290
00:28:53,192 --> 00:28:54,713
Can you give me one second, though?

291
00:28:57,326 --> 00:29:02,080
Hey, it's me, the know-it-all.

292
00:29:02,731 --> 00:29:05,724
- What are you doing here?
- I got something for you, too.

293
00:29:07,537 --> 00:29:08,657
Some flowers.

294
00:29:10,819 --> 00:29:13,343
<u>Daisy Miller</u> by Henry James.

295
00:29:13,452 --> 00:29:15,904
<u>Dandelion Wine</u> by Ray Bradbury.

296
00:29:16,625 --> 00:29:18,728
<u>White Oleander</u>, Janet Fitch.

297
00:29:21,079 --> 00:29:22,940
Very clever.

298
00:29:25,114 --> 00:29:27,165
How did you know I work here?

299
00:29:27,276 --> 00:29:30,619
I just joined the Board,
I saw you coming out of our meeting.

300
00:29:31,740 --> 00:29:33,792
You could have mentioned
that in the elevator.

301
00:29:37,215 --> 00:29:41,750
If we'd met in a taller building,
I'd of had time to cover that.

302
00:29:45,724 --> 00:29:49,398
I don't know about you, but...
I'm ready for some donating.

303
00:29:50,339 --> 00:29:52,211
Great, I'll be here.

304
00:29:52,250 --> 00:29:55,805
No way, I'd like for you to accept
books on behalf of the Library.

305
00:29:55,924 --> 00:29:58,387
- Oh, no, I can't do that.
- Yes, you can.

306
00:29:58,458 --> 00:30:00,779
No, I... I don't want my photo taken.

307
00:30:00,890 --> 00:30:02,461
Don't worry, you look stunning.

308
00:30:02,582 --> 00:30:05,785
It's not about vanity, I just don't
like people taking my photograph.

309
00:30:08,317 --> 00:30:11,810
Suit yourself, if you won't accept them,
I won't donate 'em.

310
00:30:11,931 --> 00:30:15,785
- You wouldn't do that.
- I will, I'll even have a book burning.

311
00:30:18,207 --> 00:30:22,313
I just... I don't like having
my photos taken, Ellis.

312
00:30:23,903 --> 00:30:26,496
Okay, fine, fine. Here's an alternative.

313
00:30:27,957 --> 00:30:29,238
Let me take you out tomorrow.

314
00:30:31,840 --> 00:30:34,763
Okay... that's impossible.

315
00:30:41,009 --> 00:30:43,502
All right, well, I'll just pack
up the books then, that's fine.

316
00:30:47,086 --> 00:30:48,669
Where?

317
00:30:52,030 --> 00:30:53,833
Some place you've never been.

318
00:30:55,074 --> 00:30:57,846
Well, if it's in this city,
that's unlikely.

319
00:30:59,127 --> 00:31:00,557
Try me.

320
00:31:02,751 --> 00:31:04,914
<i>You can leave your boots at
the front when you're done,</i>

321
00:31:04,943 --> 00:31:07,369
- I'll be right outside.
- We will, thank you, Tom.

322
00:31:07,457 --> 00:31:08,557
All right.

323
00:31:12,551 --> 00:31:14,854
All right... I give up.

324
00:31:17,026 --> 00:31:22,612
In the first year of the Gold Rush, about
60,000 people came to San Francisco by ship.

325
00:31:22,721 --> 00:31:26,605
And a lot of them hightailed straight
into the hills leaving their boats behind.

326
00:31:27,226 --> 00:31:30,259
Hundreds of boats were left onshore.

327
00:31:30,950 --> 00:31:34,653
Downtown San Francisco was
built right on top of them.

328
00:31:34,763 --> 00:31:35,765
I didn't know that.

329
00:31:36,144 --> 00:31:41,840
Now... City Services found this when they were
digging when they were digging for a utility line.

330
00:31:43,393 --> 00:31:47,292
- My God.
- Isn't it something?

331
00:31:48,377 --> 00:31:50,819
- Is... is that...?
- Yeah, that's a boat.

332
00:31:51,381 --> 00:31:55,884
Oh! Wow! This is incredible.

333
00:31:56,005 --> 00:31:58,819
So, we had the digging stopped immediately,
of course, because

334
00:31:58,869 --> 00:32:01,480
we want this made
available to the public.

335
00:32:01,550 --> 00:32:02,277
- "We"

336
00:32:02,304 --> 00:32:05,207
- San Francisco Historical
Preservation Society.

337
00:32:05,284 --> 00:32:07,317
Oh, let me guess, you're on the board.

338
00:32:07,396 --> 00:32:10,579
Yeah, well, they'll...
they'll let anyone on the Board these days.

339
00:32:18,988 --> 00:32:22,151
So, how did you come by
your fortune, anyway... inheritance?

340
00:32:22,912 --> 00:32:27,096
Luck.
I was a math major in college, and

341
00:32:27,175 --> 00:32:31,029
in my spare time I developed an
algorithm for analyzing climate data,

342
00:32:31,711 --> 00:32:36,445
but my roommate figured out that it could
also be used to make economic forecasts.

343
00:32:36,556 --> 00:32:39,067
So he started a company in our dorm room,

344
00:32:39,147 --> 00:32:43,573
<i>sold it 3 years later and then
with his half he retired to Fiji.</i>

345
00:32:43,682 --> 00:32:46,895
And with my half, I'm...
ya know, I'm doing this.

346
00:32:46,965 --> 00:32:49,097
Your... your job is giving away money.

347
00:32:49,208 --> 00:32:52,632
Yeah, that's right, but... but if you want to
make a real difference in this world, it's a...

348
00:32:52,741 --> 00:32:55,585
it's a lot harder than it seems.

349
00:32:58,197 --> 00:33:00,098
What about you, Jenny?

350
00:33:06,125 --> 00:33:08,136
I own a dog.

351
00:33:10,019 --> 00:33:11,019
Well.

352
00:33:11,641 --> 00:33:13,071
I should be getting back.

353
00:33:13,663 --> 00:33:14,973
I thought we were having lunch.

354
00:33:16,224 --> 00:33:19,778
It's too late, Ellis,
I only have an hour.

355
00:33:23,992 --> 00:33:25,865
Let me at least walk you back.

356
00:33:30,640 --> 00:33:34,973
Thank you for all of this, but..
But you should know I'm moving.

357
00:33:41,259 --> 00:33:45,835
I have an idea.
I'll tell you a joke, and if you laugh,

358
00:33:46,645 --> 00:33:49,268
you have to go out with me
one more again before you move away.

359
00:33:49,348 --> 00:33:53,742
And if you don't laugh, I'll know we're
incompatible and I'll gladly give up.

360
00:33:53,853 --> 00:33:57,317
- That must be one helluva joke.
- It's the funniest in human history.

361
00:33:57,386 --> 00:34:01,391
But it's subtle, sophisticated,
so you probably won't even get it.

362
00:34:02,040 --> 00:34:03,192
Yeah, probably not.

363
00:34:04,143 --> 00:34:05,144
Do you like baseball?

364
00:34:05,805 --> 00:34:07,997
- Yeah, I love it.
- Good. So...

365
00:34:09,177 --> 00:34:14,483
One day at Fenway Park,
Ted Williams... Do you know who he was?

366
00:34:14,563 --> 00:34:18,885
Oh, c'mon, the Thumper,
current batting average .344, right?

367
00:34:18,934 --> 00:34:21,331
What? Yeah, that Ted Williams.

368
00:34:21,440 --> 00:34:23,742
Anyway, so, he's hangin' around Fenway and

369
00:34:23,862 --> 00:34:26,766
this horse walks up and says,
"I want to play for the Sox."

370
00:34:26,766 --> 00:34:28,807
- An actual horse?
- An actual horse.

371
00:34:28,947 --> 00:34:30,969
Ted's like, "Okay, what can you do?"

372
00:34:31,070 --> 00:34:33,943
And the horse says, "I can hit just
like you, only a whole lot better ".

373
00:34:34,052 --> 00:34:38,007
So, he picks up the bat with
his teeth and Ted's like, "Okay",

374
00:34:38,257 --> 00:34:40,219
and he throws him a few,
and sure enough...

375
00:34:40,849 --> 00:34:41,650
goong, goong, goong!

376
00:34:43,211 --> 00:34:44,262
Into the bleachers.

377
00:34:45,103 --> 00:34:48,807
So, Ted's like,
"Whoa! What else can you do?"

378
00:34:48,878 --> 00:34:51,019
And the horse says,
"Well, I can play shortstop."

379
00:34:51,030 --> 00:34:54,387
So, Ted hits him a few
ground balls and sure enough.

380
00:34:54,487 --> 00:34:56,385
He's a "vacuum cleaner"?

381
00:34:57,554 --> 00:35:01,050
Yeah, so Ted's like,
"Whoa! Can you pitch?"

382
00:35:01,130 --> 00:35:02,733
And the horse just
looks at him and says,

383
00:35:02,831 --> 00:35:06,356
"Pitch? Who ever heard
of a horse pitching?"

384
00:35:12,572 --> 00:35:14,929
Yeah! Yes!

385
00:35:14,954 --> 00:35:19,989
Ladies and gentlemen,
the Lady has been conquered.

386
00:35:21,360 --> 00:35:24,213
That's the worst joke I've
ever heard in my entire life.

387
00:35:24,324 --> 00:35:26,275
- Thank you.
- It wasn't a compliment.

388
00:35:26,666 --> 00:35:29,949
Dinner, Tuesday, my place, 303-18th Street.

389
00:35:31,400 --> 00:35:32,402
Eight o'clock.

390
00:35:34,599 --> 00:35:35,833
Fine.

391
00:35:46,666 --> 00:35:48,827
<i>Good morning, Miss Larson,
good to see you again.</i>

392
00:35:48,907 --> 00:35:51,451
<i>- Good morning.
- So, what can we do for you today?</i>

393
00:35:51,570 --> 00:35:53,643
I'd like to add another
signee to my account.

394
00:35:53,753 --> 00:35:57,175
- May I ask the reason?
- I'll be traveling for a while.

395
00:35:57,867 --> 00:35:59,027
Traveling, huh?

396
00:35:59,759 --> 00:36:03,052
Okay, I'll get the paperwork,
I'll be right back.

397
00:36:17,376 --> 00:36:19,918
All of these companies
rate very highly with us.

398
00:36:20,028 --> 00:36:22,101
What's this, the Haloid
Photographic Company?

399
00:36:22,170 --> 00:36:25,023
They've been around 50 years,
they make photo paper and equipment.

400
00:36:25,153 --> 00:36:28,056
They're developing something called
"electro photography".

401
00:36:28,117 --> 00:36:31,740
Could revolutionize the business,
but you won't see any immediate returns.

402
00:36:31,820 --> 00:36:34,023
- Could be a few years away.
- That's all right.

403
00:36:34,753 --> 00:36:36,585
I'd hate to see you tie up your money.

404
00:36:37,306 --> 00:36:38,608
I'm patient.

405
00:36:39,548 --> 00:36:41,190
What do you know,
they changed their name.

406
00:36:41,590 --> 00:36:42,601
They're now called...

407
00:36:45,003 --> 00:36:47,376
What the heck, it starts
with an "X", it's...

408
00:36:48,036 --> 00:36:50,309
It's Greek, it's pronounced "XEROX".

409
00:36:51,260 --> 00:36:52,661
Xerox.

410
00:36:54,083 --> 00:36:57,327
<i>So, we can start with the signature card.</i>

411
00:36:58,847 --> 00:37:01,510
- What is the name of the co-signer?
- Susan Fleisher.

412
00:37:01,630 --> 00:37:07,085
- Susan, what, F-I-e...
- I-s-h-e-r.

413
00:37:09,719 --> 00:37:11,039
Now, I made you some salmon.

414
00:37:11,760 --> 00:37:16,005
This no eating nonsense just won't
do if you are a proper farm dog.

415
00:37:16,945 --> 00:37:20,088
I want you to eat every last bite,
do you understand me?

416
00:37:22,521 --> 00:37:25,273
Oh, there we go.

417
00:37:51,070 --> 00:37:54,634
Hello? Ellis?

418
00:37:59,398 --> 00:38:01,760
- Am I interrupting?
- Hey!

419
00:38:03,313 --> 00:38:07,065
- I was afraid you got cold feet.
- No, no, just trouble getting a cab.

420
00:38:07,836 --> 00:38:08,838
- Hey.
- Hi.

421
00:38:12,422 --> 00:38:13,922
Can I take your coat?

422
00:38:14,583 --> 00:38:15,706
Okay.

423
00:38:18,427 --> 00:38:21,722
Uh, your... your place it's, uh...

424
00:38:21,851 --> 00:38:23,972
- Unfinished?
- Yes!

425
00:38:24,052 --> 00:38:27,686
Uh, I noticed that part,
it's sort of an artistic choice?

426
00:38:28,643 --> 00:38:32,612
No, I have to paint and plaster
and do all the wiring stuff,

427
00:38:32,672 --> 00:38:37,867
but I'm doing it all myself, so,
it's gonna take a little while.

428
00:38:37,916 --> 00:38:39,938
- I think your food is burning.
- Ah!

429
00:38:44,137 --> 00:38:46,626
So, make yourself comfortable.

430
00:38:47,215 --> 00:38:48,427
<i>Sit down, relax.</i>

431
00:38:50,268 --> 00:38:51,302
Okay.

432
00:38:54,753 --> 00:38:57,856
What is it... that you're cooking?

433
00:38:58,418 --> 00:39:02,811
Well, it's a delicacy,
which to be honest, is not for everyone.

434
00:39:05,074 --> 00:39:06,376
I hope you like it.

435
00:39:08,126 --> 00:39:10,168
- Are you ready?
- Would you like a drum roll?

436
00:39:12,521 --> 00:39:13,523
<i>Voila!</i>

437
00:39:14,873 --> 00:39:17,467
It was between this
and stuffed quail.

438
00:39:17,907 --> 00:39:19,389
Please do not tell me
you're disappointed.

439
00:39:19,498 --> 00:39:22,931
- I... I'm truly overjoyed!
- Yes!

440
00:39:23,983 --> 00:39:25,394
- Dig in.
- Okay.

441
00:39:30,248 --> 00:39:31,034
Well?

442
00:39:31,059 --> 00:39:34,197
Well, it's perfect, just
the music is painful.

443
00:39:35,003 --> 00:39:38,418
- You don't like jazz?
- No, I love jazz, this is something else.

444
00:39:42,190 --> 00:39:45,795
My mom grew up in Maine,
she's is a real New Englander.

445
00:39:45,804 --> 00:39:48,657
Sweet, but tough as nails.

446
00:39:49,918 --> 00:39:55,974
My dad, on the other hand...
has his head in the stars... literally.

447
00:39:56,175 --> 00:39:59,568
He's an astronomer,
just retired from Stanford.

448
00:40:00,539 --> 00:40:04,083
His claim to fame was that he
discovered an unusual comet.

449
00:40:04,384 --> 00:40:06,224
Unusual, in what way?

450
00:40:06,326 --> 00:40:09,056
Well, it has a mathematically
proven perigee.

451
00:40:09,157 --> 00:40:14,041
So, based on his calculation, it will
pass by Earth in the winter of 1981.

452
00:40:14,643 --> 00:40:16,516
- Did it?
- No.

453
00:40:16,775 --> 00:40:23,385
No, it did not, but, that didn't stop
him from looking for it every year.

454
00:40:23,452 --> 00:40:26,617
It was a kind of ritual we
had when I was growing up.

455
00:40:27,887 --> 00:40:29,619
My dad is still looking.

456
00:40:33,132 --> 00:40:36,365
Well, one more glass of
wine and may see it.

